ents to high levels of government, Carvin writes with both authority and urgency. Her book presents an "insider’s look" at the issues facing the Canadian security and intelligence community. Timely and accessible, Stand on Guard will be required reading for scholars, practitioners, and any Canadian concerned about national security in the twenty-first century.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aNational securityzCanada. 4aDISCOUNT-C. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / World / Canadian.2bisacsh  aCanadian foreign policy.  acyber-threats.  aeconomic national security.  aespionage.  aforeign influence, disinformation.  aintelligence.  anational security.  aterrorism.  aviolent extremism.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311073922040uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978148753472140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781487534721423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781487534721/original  a978-3-11-073922-0  University of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2021b2021  aGBV-deGruyter-alles